segments.text: And you see that as sort of the future trend.
And I imagine academics everywhere, but especially at Texas A&M.
Do you think there is a perception of molding the A&M system as something that has a distinctive A&M character to it?
In other words, that our member institutions will become Texas A&M?
No.
I don't believe so.
I hope not.
Yeah.
On the other hand, well, another way to put that is I don't see our other universities becoming branch campuses of Texas A&M University.
But you know, chancellors come and go, and boards come and go, and maybe in the future people have a different idea.
That's my view.

that each of those institutions has its own set of opportunities it has its own special character it has its own kinds of constituencies that it serves and i want to see them develop those areas of advantage that they have and they are different the other side though as you'll see from the system definition here there are many aspects of the of the

One of those is leadership development.

All four of those are straight-out growths of Texas A&M University's tradition as a land-grant institution and as an institution that produces leaders.
Any other qualities like that you think are programs that you would expect to see infused?

I don't think so.
I think one thing that

Now, when you educate people to become engineers, the basic education comes at the undergraduate level, because that's where you cover the broad field and you have the basic preparation in math and science and so on.
